`ctx-run <dir> "<task>"` — the one-command entry point for a billed cage
session, wrapping `ctx_cage::lifecycle::execute`. Agent auth is the
operator's Claude Code subscription; typing `ctx-run` itself is the spend
authorization (no `--allow-spend` flag exists here, unlike lower-level
cage tooling).

Reads an optional `~/.config/ctx/env` (via `load_env_file`) that must be
mode `0600` when present — refuses to run otherwise, since it may hold
`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`. That file's `CTX_AGENT_CMD`/`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` are
injected only into the child `ctx-scan --update` process used for the
post-run summary refresh, never into the cage or shell itself.

After a successful session (`outcome.exit_code == 0`), prompts
interactively (`confirm_summarize`) whether to regenerate context
summaries — but only if stdin is a real terminal (`is_terminal()`,
matching the PTY relay discipline from ADR-048); non-interactive runs
default to "no" and print a manual `ctx-scan --update --approve` hint
instead. `--skip-summarize` bypasses the prompt entirely. Refresh failure
is never fatal — the session's deliverable already landed by that point.

`warn_if_no_hooks` checks for `.claude/settings.json` in the target and
warns (doesn't fail) if absent, since without it the context-chain hook
won't lead the session.

Sibling binaries (`ctx-verify`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-scan`) are resolved
via `current_exe()`'s directory, overridable with `CTX_VERIFY_BIN` /
`CTX_CONTEXT_BIN` / `CTX_SCAN_BIN` env vars — same resolution convention
as `ctx-cage`. `Mode` is `Task(String)` or `Interactive`; exactly one of
`--interactive` or a task string must be supplied, enforced in
`pick_mode`.